  "articleSummary": "This article argues that replacing `Map` with `WeakMap` in JavaScript can eliminate memory leaks caused by strong references to objects that should be garbage collected. It explains that `WeakMap` holds weak references to its keys, allowing the garbage collector to clean up both the key and its associated value when no other references exist, with constraints like no iteration and object-only keys. The tutorial-style piece targets JavaScript developers building long-running applications (e.g., SPAs, dashboards) and uses metaphors like \"iron grip\" and \"temporary citizens\" to contrast strong vs. weak references. Key use cases include attaching metadata to DOM nodes, private data patterns, and memoization, where cleanup is automatic.",
